%md
#The sciDataset
The purpose of this notebook is to introduce the user to the concept and use of SciSpark's **sciDataset**.
Topics to be addressed here include:
* the anatomy of the sciDataset
* ingesting data from [netCDF](http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/netcdf/) files into sciDatasets and the sRDD
* introduction to operations available for data within the sciDataset
* modifying data within the sciDataset
* passing an sRDD of sciDatasets from the Scala/Java environment to the Python environment
* visualization of data in the Python environment

To address these topics, a simple analysis of rainfall data will be conducted. More specifically, using hourly rate data, 6- hourly rainfall accumulations will be found.The data used in this notebook is the [Tropical Rainfall Measuring Mission (TRMM) 0.25째 x 0.25째degree 3-hourly dataset](http://disc.sci.gsfc.nasa.gov/precipitation/documentation/TRMM_README/TRMM_3B42_readme.shtml). 
This data is shipped with the Scispark Docker VM.

###Reference
* Wilson B., R. Palamuttam, K. Whitehall, C. Mattmann, A. Goodman, M. Boustani, S. Shah, P. Zimdars, and P. Ramirez, 2016. SciSpark: Highly Interactive In-Memory Science Data Analytics. 2016 IEEE International Conference on Big Data (Big Data) (in review).

%md ## The sciDataset The **sciDataset** is a self-documenting collection of named N-dimensional arrays, with attributes, developed for sRDD transformations. The global and per-variable attributes in sciDatasets are designed to support the [netCDF Climate Forecast (CF)](http://cfconventions.org/) metadata conventions for the data read from NetCDF files. Through the SciSpark context, data can be loaded from network Common Data Form (netCDF) files directly into the sRDD.
![The sciDataset architecture](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/sciDataset.png) Figure 1: The sciDataset architecture

**Architecture of the sciDataset** The **sciDataset** consists of two hash tables. 1. The global attribute table. The global attribute table records metadata about the source dataset/file as key-value pairs (string keys and scalar values) for e.g. the coordinate system used, the creator of the dataset, etc. 2. The variables table. The variables table stores one or more SciSpark **Variable** objects each consisting of an N-dim. numeric array, and its set of attributes (e.g. unit, offset, coordinates, missing values, etc.) as read from the source dataset. The N-dim numeric array within the **Variable** object is the **AbstractTensor**. The **AbstractTensor** abstracts the backend Java library being used for the N-dim numeric array operations and computations. Currently SciSpark is backed by two Java N-dim array libraries, [Breeze](https://github.com/scalanlp/breeze) - a library for numerical processing, and [ND4J](http://nd4j.org/userguide) - a full scientific computing libary. SciSpark supports ND4J in the backend by default.

%md ##Working with the sciDataset Both the global and variable tables of the **sciDataset** are accessible from within sRDD transformation functions. * The (global) metadata fields within the **sciDataset** can be edited to update or append new attributes. * Deep copying of the **sciDataset** is available. * Array arithmetic and logical operations can be invoked on individual **Variable** objects of the **sciDataset** to change them or to compute new **Variable** objects as needed. If a new **Variable** object is computed, it can be added to the existing **sciDataset**, thus increasing the number of **Variable** objects within that **sciDataset** or it can be inserted into a new **sciDataset** object. View the "Operations available on Variable objects" section for more details on this. In that the **Variable** object contains an N-dim numeric array (the **AbstractTensor**) and key-value pairs (string keys and scalar values) of attributes, the attributes component of the **Variable** object can also be updated and / or appended to. This is a good practice to register changes to the data during analysis. * Writing the contents of the **sciDataset** to disk is also available directly and/or through an sRDD transformation. In this case, the data are written in netCDF3 format to the HDFS1. For example, most of the datasets contain the datetime in the filename. This information can be parsed while the data is being loaded into the ***sciDataset*** (or at anytime) and added as a metadata field in the ***sciDataset*** global attributes. Such data can prove to be very useful later during analysis if sequentially is required. Some common methods that operate on the **sciDataset** can be viewed in the table below. Please refer to the [SciSpark Dataset API](https://scispark.jpl.nasa.gov/api/#org.dia.core.SciDataset) for the full list.
sciDataset common methods Description
setName Set the name of the sciDataset.
attr Prints the attribute from the sciDataset.
toString Prints all the (global) attributes from the sciDataset.
update Adds a new Variable or attribute to the existing sciDataset. Can also be used for updating existing Variable or attribute.
insertAttribute Adds a new (global) attribute to the existing sciDataset.
insertVariable Adds a new Variable into the existing sciDataset.
writeToNetCDF Writes the contents of the sciDataset to a netCDF file.
writeToNetCDF Writes the contents of the sciDataset to a netCDF file.

1The netCDF files are not directly written to HDFS. In reality the netCDF files are written to local disk, then copied to the HDFS location.

%md ##Operations available on Variable objects These operations occur on the N-dim numerical array - the **AbstractTensor**- within the **Variable**. ####(1) Relational operators Relational operators are useful for comparing values. The end user can determine which **Variable** in the **sciDataset** (i.e. the **AbstractTensor** associated with that **Variable**) to perform the operation on. If no **Variable** in the **sciDataset** is explicitly identified to use in the operation, the operation will occur on the *varInUse* by default. The valid relational operators for **Variables** are given in the table below.
Relational Operator Description
< less than a user-defined value
<= less than or equals to a user-defined value
> greater than a user-defined value
>= greater than of equals a user-defined value
:=

equals to a user-defined value
!= not equals to a user-defined value

An example of the syntax using the "greater than or equals to" operator is given as: ``` val minPrecip = 0.1 val x = sRDD.map(sciDS => sciDS("precip") >= minPrecip) ``` A common use case of using relational operators is associated with masking data. There are two masking functions available for **Variable** objects. * **mask** applies a masking function on the **AbstractTensor** of the given **Variable** * **setMask** sets the default mask alue for the particular **Variable**
####(2) Arithmetic operations Arithmetic operators maybe useful for tasks such as converting units, determining totals within time periods or finding averages. The end user can determine which **Variable** object(s) in the **sciDataset** to perform the computation on. Operators are provided for both in-place operators (i.e. the original **AbstractTensor** associated with the **Variable** is changed) and copy operations (a copy of the input data is made ahead of performing the calculation, and this what is returned). For scalar operations, the scalar must be represented as a Double. The table of available arithmetic operators are provided in the table below.
Arithmetic Operator Description
+ In-place scalar or matrix element-wise addition.
- In-place scalar or matrix element-wise subtraction.
* In-place scalar or matrix element-wise multiplication.
/ In-place scalar or matrix element-wise division.
+=

Scalar or matrix addition element-wise copy operation.
-= Scalar or matrix element-wise subtraction copy operation.
/*= Scalar or matrix element-wise multiplication copy operation.
/= Scalar or matrix element-wise division copy operation.
** Matrix multiplication2.

####(3) Statistical operations
Statistical Operators Description
mean Computes the mean along the given axis of the Variable.
detrend
std Computes the standard deviation along the given axis of the Variable.
skew

####(4) Other methods available for Variable objects These methods operate directly on the **Variable**. The table below provides some common methods. Please refer to the [SciSpark Variable API](https://scispark.jpl.nasa.gov/api/#org.dia.core.Variable) for more details.
Some common methods available for the Variable Description
dims Returns dimensions of the Variable.
toString Prints the attributes of the Variable.
copy Copies the existing Variable into a new Variable.

Note that: to access the **AbstractTensor** of a **Variable** use. ``` sciDS(Var)() ``` whereas to access the data in the **Variable** use ``` sciDS(Var).data ``` The latter returns an Array of Doubles.
####(5) Other methods available for the AbstractTensor These methods operate directly on the **AbstractTensor** as opposed to the **Variable** i.e. the syntax follows *sciDS(Var)().*.
Other methods available for the AbstractTensor Description
rows Returns number of rows for a 2D AbstractTensor.
cols Returns number of cols for a 2D AbstractTensor.
min, max Returns the min / max value in the AbstractTensor respectively.
reshape Reshapes the AbstractTensor according to the input dims
stack Stacks the current AbstractTensor ontop of the input AbstractTensor in row-ordered fashion.
labelComponents Returns an AbstractTensor with labels of contiguous areas according to the input mask.

Please refer to the [SciSpark AbstractTensor API](https://scispark.jpl.nasa.gov/api/#org.dia.tensors.AbstractTensor) for the full list of methods and more details on usage.
2Linear algebra operation

val accu3hrly = labels.map(p => {
    val varname = "pcp"
	val precipAccStr = "(" + varname +" * 3.0)"
	val precipAccTensor = p(varname) * 3.0
		val precipAccVar = new Variable("precip3hrlyAcc", "float", precipAccTensor.data,
			p(varname).shape(), List(("Calculation",  precipAccStr)), p(varname).dims)
	precipAccVar.insertAttributes(("long_name", "precipitation 3hrlyAccumulation"))
    precipAccVar.insertAttributes(("units", "mm"))		
	p.insertVariable(("precip3hrlyAcc", precipAccVar))
  })

%md ## Maintaining time in the sRDD When the data are read into the **sciDatasets** into memory into the sRDD, they are collated in groups and distributed according to the number of paritions to be used. Actions are then performed in parallel on the data in each parition. From this process, we can see that there is no guarantee that the data in each partition or the sRDD are in any coherent order. However, maintaining a timeseries throughout a set of calculations maybe prudent for *some* analysis. Given the inherent distributed environment, this is not a trivial task. The SciSpark approach copies the data and creates tuples of consecutive **sciDatasets** for all the **sciDatasets** in a given sRDD. ![maintaining time in the sRDD](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/groupByApproach.png) Figure 2: Illustration of the maintenance of the time sequence in the sRDD
For example, assuming that the global attribute representing the datatime is avaiable in each **sciDataset**, inorder to maintain the timeseries, a copy of the data is generated, and tuples between consecutive datetimes created. For example, for the dates 2016060100, 2016060101, 2016060102, 2016060103, 2016060104, 2016060105, the following linkages will occur: ``` Map(Date -> 2016060100) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060101) Map(Date -> 2016060101) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060102) Map(Date -> 2016060102) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060103) Map(Date -> 2016060103) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060104) Map(Date -> 2016060104) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060105) ``` In this way, time between consecutive frames will always be maintained, and the timeseries.

    p._1.setName(newname)
    p._1
})

%md ##Sharing Data Between Scala/Java And Python in SciSpark notebooks At this point, given the notebook environment, one may wish to visualize the data *while* it is still in the sRDD leveraging Python's matplotlib. To do this, one needs to pass the data from the Scala environment to the Python environment. This is done leveraging the Py4J Gateway and the "Object exchange" property in Apache Zeppelin that shares the **sparkcontext** and **SciSparkContext** between environments. We can pass the entire sRDD using the "Object exchange" thus reducing the need for I/O inorder to visualize by leveraging the [PySpark MLLIB common library](https://spark.apache.org/docs/1.5.0/api/python/_modules/pyspark/mllib/common.html).
In general, to put an object from the Scala/ Java environment use: ``` val myVar = ... z.put("myVarName", myVar) ``` To get the object from Python use: ``` %pyspark myVar = z.get("myVarName") ``` The reverse is also true.
The **sciDataset** is not directly passable through the Py4J gateway. The Py4J gateway supports accessing some Java collection and array in Python, but not all. See the [Py4J documentation](https://www.py4j.org/advanced_topics.html#accessing-java-collections-and-arrays-from-python) for more details. Py4J by default passes the objects by reference (as opposed to value) within the JVM. Notwithstanding, SciSpark is written in a Scala environment and thus the data must be converted to a Java environment then passed through the gateway. SciSpark provides an API to aid this passing of the Scala **AbstractTensor** array to an Java ArrayBuffer object, and passing that data through the gateway.

Sharing Data Between Scala/Java And Python in SciSpark notebooks

At this point, given the notebook environment, one may wish to visualize the data while it is still in the sRDD leveraging Python's matplotlib. To do this, one needs to pass the data from the Scala environment to the Python environment. This is done leveraging the Py4J Gateway and the “Object exchange” property in Apache Zeppelin that shares the sparkcontext and SciSparkContext between environments. We can pass the entire sRDD using the “Object exchange” thus reducing the need for I/O inorder to visualize by leveraging the PySpark MLLIB common library.


In general, to put an object from the Scala/ Java environment use:

val myVar = ...
z.put("myVarName", myVar)

To get the object from Python use:

%pyspark
myVar = z.get("myVarName")

The reverse is also true.


The sciDataset is not directly passable through the Py4J gateway. The Py4J gateway supports accessing some Java collection and array in Python, but not all. See the Py4J documentation for more details. Py4J by default passes the objects by reference (as opposed to value) within the JVM. Notwithstanding, SciSpark is written in a Scala environment and thus the data must be converted to a Java environment then passed through the gateway. SciSpark provides an API to aid this passing of the Scala AbstractTensor array to an Java ArrayBuffer object, and passing that data through the gateway.

paragraphs.title: On the Python side to access the data:

%pyspark
from pyspark.mllib.common import _java2py
import numpy

sliding6hrlyPy = z.get("sliding6hrlyList")

pythonRDD = _java2py(sc, sliding6hrlyPy)

def convert_to_numpy(aList):
    '''
        aList is  [javaDataBuffer, Variable.shape, dtime] in the sRDD
    '''
    dt = numpy.dtype('d')
    dt = dt.newbyteorder('>')
    da = numpy.frombuffer(aList[0], dtype=dt)
    da.shape = (aList[1][1], aList[1][2])
    return (da, int(aList[2]))
    
listOfNumpy = pythonRDD.map(lambda t: convert_to_numpy(t))
collectedListOfNumpy = listOfNumpy.collect()
